<br>
You are freakin' korrect about this bill attracting the attention of every fringe nutcase out there on the internet!<br>
<br>
You're probably right that the language should have been more delicately phrased.<br>
<br>
I am certain that the phrase 'extraterrestrial weapons&quot; as used was definitely in the same sense as the Clarke phrase.<br>
<br>
Here is a variety of references using similar terms:<br>
<br>
======================================<br>
The Times of London <br>
June 30, 2001   <br>
The Last Frontier: Space is Key to Bush Defense Plan  <br>
<br>
&quot;Also facing the axe is the idea that space should be free of offensive weapons to avoid an <!--EZCODE FONT START--><span style="color:yellow;">extraterrestrial arms race</span><!--EZCODE FONT END-->. Under the new thinking in Washington, space is likely to be viewed as a legitimate battleground, if only to ensure the protection of America’s rapidly growing network of military and commercial satellites.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Despite their fears of losing the advantage in space, both the United States and the Soviet Union exercised great restraint in this realm. Both sides realized that they had more to lose than to gain from such competition. As tempting as it was to contemplate gaining a military edge in space, the risks of an <!--EZCODE FONT START--><span style="color:yellow;">extraterrestrial arms race</span><!--EZCODE FONT END--> were even greater.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Rather than elevate the Cold War competition into space, Washington and Moscow agreed to both tacit and formal constraints on <!--EZCODE FONT START--><span style="color:yellow;">extraterrestrial military activities</span><!--EZCODE FONT END-->. These agreements included the 1967 Outer Space Treaty, which bans the placement of weapons of mass destruction in space or on celestial bodies, and the 1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty, which prohibits interference with monitoring satellites.&quot;<br>
=============================================<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
====================================== <br>
Foreign Affairs Journal<br>
May/June 2001 <br>
----------------<br>
Lost in Space:<br>
The Misguided Drive Toward Antisatellite Weapons <br>
<br>
&quot; The opposition was so great, in fact, that SDI's proponents rarely publicly defended the program in straightforward and simple terms -- that is, as a way to achieve security through <!--EZCODE FONT START--><span style="color:yellow;">extraterrestrial dominance</span><!--EZCODE FONT END-->.&quot;<br>
=========================================<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
==========================================<br>
The NATO School (SHAPE) POLARIS<br>
A publication of Nato Schools Educational Technology and Research Department<br>
Arms Control News Round-Up, April 8th, 2002<br>
Issue Number 11<br>
<br>
&quot;CHINA WARNS AGAINST SPACE ARMS RACE<br>
 In a veiled reference to recent US policies Qiao said that military strategies to gain an upper hand could spark an <!--EZCODE FONT START--><span style="color:yellow;">extraterrestrial arms race</span><!--EZCODE FONT END-->.&quot; <br>
========================================<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
=========================================<br>
NATURE<br>
29th December 1988: Vol 336 No 6201 pp699-792 <br>
 <br>
&quot;  Is the space environment at risk? 725 <br>
G. B. Field, M. J. Rees &amp; D. N. Spergel <br>
The huge potential of space for science, exploration and peaceful applications could be jeopardized by debris in Earth orbit, and by an <!--EZCODE FONT START--><span style="color:yellow;">extraterrestrial arms race</span><!--EZCODE FONT END-->. <br>
doi:10.1038/336725a0&quot;<br>
