<br>
  Just curious what you two do, career wise.  Your posts are enlightening and I'm just curious what you do at work.  And sorry... I know the question is off thread.<br>
<br>
  As far as DK and his ban exotic weapons from space bill, don't agree with it.  The research and deployment of these types of weapons is on going and the deployment has ... well I'll let you two fill in the blanks.  I'm fully in the &quot;America must dominate space&quot; camp.<br>
<br>
  AC - DK probably has no idea what is being worked on unless he sits on a Congressional committee that oversees the military branch or gov't agency working on these weapons.  These committees have classified briefings where this kind of information is discussed.  And only a few Congressmen/Congresswomen have the pre-requisite security clearance and are &quot;read&quot; into these programs to know what's going on.  <br>
<br>
  If I've insulted your intelligence, apologize in advance. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=atomicconspiracy>Atomic Conspiracy</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 297<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/12/04 12:58 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=990.topic&index=25>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: RE</span><hr size=1> I am a geologist. I own a consulting business that specializes in the geology of erosion control, especially in evaluating risk factors for various projects. I am also an Adjunct Professor of Earth Science at a state university. <br>
<br>
I was an Army aviator many years ago, and eventually switched to Air Defense Artillery after I lost my medical clearance (if you can't join 'em, beat 'em). <br>
<br>
My experience with rocketry is naturally confined to relatively small solid-fuel types such as Nike Hercules, Hawk, and the accursed American version of Roland. <br>
<br>
(Actually the Hercules was enormous by SAM standards, 41 ft long and weighing better than 5 tons, but this is still puny compared to space rockets. It was a two-stage vehicle and had tremendous flight performance, but the guidance system was about what you would use in an RC model plane these days, if even that good. Also puny by current standards was the cost: $59,000 each when they were built in the late 50s.)<br>
I retired from the Army Reserve at field-grade rank in 1997. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=yales>yales</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 1400<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/12/04 9:30 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=990.topic&index=26>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://home.attbi.com/~yales/images/53invad2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: RE</span><hr size=1> Brief Bio..<br>
