 <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=yales>yales</A> at: 1/12/04 9:55 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=atomicconspiracy>Atomic Conspiracy</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 298<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/12/04 3:51 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=990.topic&index=28>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: RE</span><hr size=1> Ah, yes <br>
&quot;The nuclear-capable Nike Hercules&quot;<br>
<br>
This article goes out of its way to raise the dread specter of radioactive waste <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :evil --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/devil.gif ALT=":evil"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  being left behind in Chicago, merely by emphasizing the relevant section in a general cleanup manual for de-activated military facilities. <br>
<br>
Radioactive waste is easy to find. Any such contamination would long since have been detected and proven by people unconnected with the government.  <br>
As usual, not everyone knows that. <br>
<br>
It sounds ominous that the government will not reveal which sites had the W-31, but it really doesn't mean much since it was a known option for all of them. <br>
<br>
Because it was command-guided, the Hercules could be used against surface targets. It was probably better for this in some respects than the purpose-built Sergeant SRBM. This mission would only exist, of course, in overseas areas such as Korea and Europe, but the nuclear option is obviously more relevant for this than for air defense. <br>
<br>
Nonetheless, the nuclear Hercules did have some valid uses in air defense. The nuclear option gave it a small capability against first generation SLBMs and IRBMs. This was not at all satisfactory, but it considerably better than nothing in the context of the time. <br>
<br>
The very last US above-ground nuclear test was of a Hercules warhead. The detonation was at extreme altitude, suggesting that the missile-defense capability was still being pursued in 1963.   <br>
  <br>
The article is grossly in error in claiming a weight of 1000 pounds for the Hercules conventional warhead.  <br>
<br>
Modernized Hercules are still in use overseas with non-US forces, so the actual warhead weight remains classified to the best of my knowledge, though figures are available from many public sources.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=timberwind@nuclearspace>timberwind</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>NEP Freighter Crewman</span><br>  Posts: 63<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/14/04 8:03 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=990.topic&index=29>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   RE</span><hr size=1> AC/Yales,<br>
<br>
  My turn.  I'm a defense contractor (Lockheed Martin) living/working in Big Sky Country (Montana).  I retired from the USAF a few years back (after 20 years), as a MSgt.  Have always been a space nut (remember skipping grade school in the early 70s to watch the moon shots).  Career has been in the comm-computer field.  And out of 20 years of service, lived in Germany for just under 8 of them.<br>
<br>
  An interesting note after reading the Nike Hercules post.  Here in Montana, north of Great Falls about 90 miles &lt;Ledger exit off of I-15&gt;, is an old abandoned ABM command and control facility.  It seems the US Army built this facility in the early 70s as an alternate site for the primary ABM site in North Dakota.  The ABM treaty got in the way of it being completed (also some union problems) and work was stopped after the facility was about 40% complete.  Between 50 - 100 million dollars was spent before the work stoppage.  It now sits in a ranchers field, a monument to another time. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=dustyslaunchpad>Dustys Launchpad</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Orion Commander</span><br>  Posts: 272<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/15/04 4:16 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=990.topic&index=30>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Beagle 2 news</span><hr size=1> From the website,<br>
